Rush Hour Explorations

Assignment for PVG0038 Reproducibility in Research with a focus on data analysis using the program R

Alexander Koc (alexander.koc@slu.se)

2020-11-06

Summary

In this short report I investigate the value of adding two new features to the Kaggle bikeshare data set: hour denoting hour of day and boolean variable rush_hour to denote if the current hour is during rush hour or not. The two variables will be evaluated together with the remaining predictors by fitting a random model forest and extracting variable importance metrics.

This document and associated files required for re-running the analysis can be downloaded from: https://github.com/alkc/project-reproducibility

Data

The data set contains historical usage patterns for the Capital Bikeshare program in Washington, D.C., together with weather data. The purpose of the Kaggle competition in which this data set was made available was to forecast bike rental demand in the program (Fanaee-T and Gama 2014).

Packages

All analysis below will be conducted in the statistical programming language R (R Core Team 2020). The data exploration and model fit will rely heavily on the tidyverse family of packages (Wickham et al. 2019) and the modeling package (Kuhn 2020). Random forest models will be fit using ranger (Wright and Ziegler 2017). Correlation plot will be constructed using corrplot (Wei and Simko 2017). Other utility packages include here (Mller 2017), parallel (R Core Team 2020), forcats (Wickham 2020) and lubridate (Grolemund and Wickham 2011). For a full specification of R and package versions used in creating this document, please refer to the session info

# Create variable specification for dataset:
col_spec <- cols(
  .default = col_double(),
  datetime = col_datetime(format = ""),
  season = col_integer(),
  holiday = col_logical(),
  workingday = col_logical(),
  weather = col_factor(),
  count = col_integer()
)

bikeshare <- read_csv(here::here("data/train.csv"), col_types = col_spec)

We drop the casual and registered columns, as they add up to the count column anyway making it a linear combination of both.

bikeshare <- bikeshare %>% 
  select(-registered, -casual)

Expand season names to text labels we have the computer memory and screen real estate to spare:

bikeshare <- bikeshare %>% 
  mutate(season = map_chr(season, function(season_code) {
    
    seasons <- c("spring" = 1, "summer" = 2,  "fall" = 3, winter = "4")
    translated_name <- names(seasons[season_code])
    
    # (I guess map_chr would catch this anyway?)
    if(is.na(translated_name)) {
      err <- paste("Invalid season code:", season_code)
      stop(err)
    }
    
    return(translated_name)
    
  }))

# Convert back to factor:
bikeshare$season <- as.factor(bikeshare$season)

Expand some column names to spell out what they actually are and rename others to make data set look nicer.

bikeshare <-  bikeshare %>% 
  rename(
    date_time = datetime,
    working_day = workingday,
    temp_celcius = temp,
    feels_like_temp_celcius = atemp,
    relative_humidity = humidity,
    wind_speed = windspeed,
    total_nbr_rentals = count

Finally, the hour at which bikes are rented feels like it should have some predictive power. Split the date time into a time column:

bikeshare <- bikeshare %>% 
  mutate(hour = hour(date_time)) %>%
  select(date_time, hour, everything())

Probably good idea to create another column that specified which day of the week it is. A weekend starts after working hours on a friday, and I hypothesize there will be more bike sharing activity on a friday evening -> midnight compared to other weekdays. Out of the scope for this assignment though.

Adding new features

hour

Visualize total number of rentals by daily hour the new variable introduced earlier in code.

bikeshare %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = hour, y = total_nbr_rentals)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.1)

Clear peak of rides around rush hours. Investigate to see if there is an interaction with the workday variable.

bikeshare %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = hour, y = total_nbr_rentals, color = working_day)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.1)

Split up the plot above into two plots and the pattern becomes more clear. Rush hour peaks of course exist on working days. Weekends seem to have more bike share activity in the hours on and after midnight.

bikeshare %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = hour, y = total_nbr_rentals)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.1) +
  facet_wrap(~working_day)

rush_hour

Create new boolean variable rush_hour by intersecting all hours between 05-10 and 15-19 when working_day == TRUE:

bikeshare <- bikeshare %>% 
  mutate(rush_hour = map2_lgl(hour, working_day, function(hour, working) {
    
    # If not working day then no rush hour
    if(working == FALSE) {
      return(FALSE)
    }
    
    if((5 < hour & hour < 10) | (15 < hour & hour < 19)) {
      return(TRUE)
    }
    
    return(FALSE)
    
  }))

How does the new feature describe the data?

bikeshare %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fill = rush_hour, x = total_nbr_rentals)) + 
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Less counts distributed around 0 for rush hour hours.

Model

We will fit a random forest model using caret. Best model will be selected on basis of 5-fold cross validation. Variable importance will be assessed by extracting variable importance metrics from final model and plotting.

train_control <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats = 0, verboseIter = FALSE, allowParallel = TRUE)

Remove the date_time column and fit model using all predictor variables. Use ranger for parallel random forest model fit. Predictors are centered and scaled.

# This might take a few minutes to run!
fit_mod <- bikeshare %>% 
  select(-date_time) %>% 
  train(total_nbr_rentals ~ ., data = ., method = "ranger", trControl = train_control, preProcess = c("center", "scale"), num.threads = nbr_cores, importance = "impurity")
